   <text>
      <front>
         <p>1898 December 1: to Yates<note xml:id="ftn3-926" place="foot" n="926"> MTG HB m80/8, 67868.</note>
         </p>
      </front>
      <body>
         <p rend="end">Napier Decr. 1/98</p>
         <p>Mr. W.W. Yates</p>
         <p>My dear Sir</p>
         <p>I was not long about it, &amp; found out your plant: it is a British weed:—<hi rend="italic">Bupleurum rotundifolium</hi>, “Hare’s-ear,” also, “Thorow-wax,” with our <hi rend="italic">forefathers</hi>, meaning growing thoroughly—through &amp; through: “wax,” an old verb to live to grow (Luke II.40).</p>
         <p>The genus was considered to be injurious to cattle feeding on it, hence the name of <hi rend="italic">Bupleurum.</hi>
         </p>
         <p>Yours faithfully,</p>
         <p>W. Colenso.</p>
      </body>
   </text>
